segments.text: 6, 2000, the anniversary of D-Day, at 529 Helena, and getting ready to chat with Mr. Fred Nelson.
Mr. Nelson, would you say a sentence or two?
Let's check your mic.
Well, it's nice to have you, and it's one of those things, like I said, I feel flattered, you know, that you want me to recount the days when I was a day in and out.
All right, sir.
Nice to see you now.
Mr. Nelson, to begin with, please tell us about your growing up.
Where were you born?
Where did you go to school?
What did your parents do for a living?
How long had they lived there?
Well, we have some in common that you may not know about or I may have told you before, but I grew up in Collin County.
My parents were
sharecropping people.
And I grew up on a farm in a community called Lovejoy.
That's where I went to school until the ninth grade.
And in those days, high school ended in the 11th grade.
So after finishing at Lovejoy, I then went to Boyd High in McKinney, Texas, where I was graduated in 1930.
And as you probably will recall,
that the beginning of the Great Depression was my era.
And I didn't particularly like farm work, so I went into the music business, having been talented at piano.
We had little bands in high school.
And from that situation there, from having become a musician, so to speak,
I went on, and during the Depression, I made whatever living I could from playing around with different bands.
So from there, out of McKinney, I left somewhere probably in the mid-30s and started out on the road with various musical organizations from somewhere maybe in the
the area of the south to the east coast, and halfway to the west coast from time to time with the various types of bands.
What were the names of some of the bands you played with?
Well, one I can think of right offhand, we had our own bands, you know, and we organized, but we never did really have a name.
until I'd say in the mid-30s, I went with a band out of Waco called the Joe Buzzy Band.
B-U-Z-Z-E, Buzzy.
And we toured Texas on one-night stands, et cetera, et cetera.
And until about 1939,
I got tired of that one night stand thing and traveling over the state of Texas.
And so I left the organization and went to Fort Worth where my sister and her husband lived.
And eventually I went into, let's see, I've forgotten what the name, as I think of it,
general merchandising thing, you know.
Let's see what was the name.
I couldn't remember what the name was.
You could probably remember the name.
There was a big organization there in Fort Worth, and I worked.
Leonard, was it Leonard Brothers?
It was Dawes Crossford Street from Leonard's.
You remember what?
No, sir.
I'll remember it.
Anyway, I went into the clothing business, and so in 1940,
I had a call from one of the musicians that I played in a band with around McKinney, and he wanted to know if I'd be interested in coming to A&M and playing piano in the Aggieland Orchestra.
Well, having always wanted to go to A&M, I guess you could say I might have jumped at the chance.
And as an aside, I also had a chance at the same time to go with, at the behest of another musician I worked with before, to go to Texas Tech.
So I was considering going to Texas Tech and playing a band out there, or come to A&M.
So like I say, having always aspired to be an Aggie, I chose to come to A&M, and I came here in 1940.
Let me back up a little bit about your parents.
Do you have any idea how many acres they farmed?
Yes, I think we had 140 some odd acres.
And we farmed cotton, corn, oats.
You know, and sometimes we tried wheat, but wheat didn't grow well in that part of the country.
Which of those was the most profitable?
Cotton?
Cotton, probably so, yes.
Where did y'all gin it?
In McKinney.
And was McKinney where you went to spend money, to shop?
Yes, uh-huh.
McKinney, we were southeast of McKinney about seven miles in a community called Lovejoy.
Also a little Baptist church called Friendship where I was converted.
And then there was a funeral situation, a cemetery at Forest Grove.
And then between the two churches, Lovejoy was on the farm road out there.
Now what were your duties on that farm?
Well, I picked cotton, gathered corn, and the usual things.
But I had two older brothers who did the plowing and managing the livestock and that type of thing.
And you all plowed with mules, or did you have a tractor?
With mules.
Tractors were a novel thing in those days.
And let's see, electricity, telephone?
Well, we had a community telephone.
but no electricity, you know, lamps, coal oil lamps, and eventually you got one of those gas things, you know, the air type thing.
And where was your well, your water?
We had two wells, one for the stock at the farm on the, you know, out around the barn area, and one near the house, both of which finally went beyond the depth, you know,
water dropped off, you know.
And so we started having to haul water in.
And we, there was a creek near our place, near the community.
Was that Spring Creek or East Fork of the, or Rowlett Creek?
I believe it was probably East Fork.
And let's see.
There's a
After our water level dropped below the level of our wells, there was a place down on this what they call Wilson Creek.
It had a well on it.
The water was practically to the top of the ground.
The water level there was so, I guess it was feeding off that creek.
So we used to haul, my dad had a,
a big tank made and put it on the wagon and we'd go down there and draw water and haul it home and that's what we used.
That's how we kept water at the house.
And how did you get to school when you went into McKinney?
My dad had a car and I had two sisters who were students at the time and one of my sisters
McKinney and they had, I don't know what it was, to go to school.
Oh, so you would go to town and spend the night in town?
No, we'd drive, oh, I would drive the car, you know, and there was two or three guys from Lovejoy there that went to McKinney and really formed that, yeah.
Where did you learn to play the piano?
Well, I started sitting around...
But the piano, when I was about six or seven years old, I guess I had a natural talent.
And I just progressed from there.
From every year, I seemed to maybe improve a little bit or learn a little bit of something.
And I might say, I have often said that I started playing the piano when I was six.
And I learned by myself.
Although I had older sisters.
So you didn't have any formal piano instruction?
You didn't?
You never had a teacher outside the family?
Well,
When I was about in, I guess, maybe the fourth or fifth grade, I had a teacher who taught me for about three months.
But when the end of the school year, and when she came out of my camp, you know, and goes out there to teach.
But when the school term ended, when I was having my lessons with her,
Did you have a model?
Who were you trying to play the piano like?
No, I didn't have a, see, we didn't have a radio in that place.
And I used to, did you ever hear a singing school?
Well, we had a singing school.
And every year, this band was also a community member, had a special community out of a songbook.
So I used to make those things.
I guess I might have been the one or two, if we haven't known over a few years.
And I may have learned some things from doing that.
So were you playing gospel music first?
Yes.
Church music?
Yes.
But we didn't have a radio, you know, so we didn't get the benefit of the programs that were sent out over the radio.
And mainly I began to play songs in the songbook.
And I've never learned to read music.
Did you ever use any of the Stamps Quartet music?
Oh, yes.
There was another piano man in the community who specialized in the Stamps Quartet music.
And I never tried to compete with him because I was more inclined to the popper music.
level of music than otherwise.
So when you finished high school, you worked a little, and then you went on the road.
And about what year did you first go on the road?
Let's see.
I was 30.
I was 18.
And I have to kind of recount how far back I went on the road.
I believe that my first introduction to the popular music that I learned was when
Two friends of mine, one a country man and the other a intersex man, we used to get together and play.
And I had little small bands and we appeared in a little dance hall, you know, there in McKinney for a while.
Well, these two guys belonged to the National Choir.
And one summer, at the county picnic,
One of them, the trumpet man, approached me and said, how would you like to go to the National Guard training camp as a musician?
So my parents didn't want me to go.
I was 16 at the time.
No, was I 16?
Yeah, I guess I was still in high school the first time I went to National Guard.
I was about 16, and I went down there and played with the 16th police officers.
I couldn't read a note.
I just had to go by ear, you know, to find out what came next, so to speak.
And that was really my first introduction to the big band.
And that National Guard thing only lasted two weeks.
I didn't join the National Guard.
I was going as a substitute for a man, a member of the band in the National Guard who could not go.
So they put me into his team and so forth.
Did y'all, was your primary task to play for National Guard dances?
Yes, uh-huh.
So y'all were not playing march music?
No, we weren't.
Dance music?
Yeah.
Of course, they had a band, you know, and these people, the rest of the people were members of the band, and this was kind of an offshoot of the band, you know, various ones.
Of course, they didn't have a piano band, and they substituted me in there.
I don't know how it was expanded, but anyway, I learned a lot from going back.
I went to three different years of camp in the National Guard.
ever worry about a young Baptist boy playing dance music?
I've never heard of it.
Nobody ever?
When you went on the road with those bands, do you remember some of the towns you all went to?
Uh, with Buzz's band, we'd go out into West Texas, and, you know, they held rodeos.
Sometimes they had a three-day rodeo.
So we'd book in for three nights of dance.
And, uh, I don't know.
It was very familiar.
West Texas dance.
There's not anything out now that I can pull up, you know.
About how many were in his band?
There was nine of us, I believe, in that band, in Buzz's band.
And, uh...
What did they play?
What instruments?
We probably had three saxes, two or three trumpets, two trombones, bass, piano, and drummer.
And what kind of music did you all play?
We played, I guess, the big band stuff.
Do you remember how much pay you got?
Yeah, it was very little, about $5 an hour, something like that.
But that was pretty good pay, though, for that era.
Yeah.
How did y'all travel?
The band leader owned the bus, and he drove it.
Although, finally, the bass man, yeah, the bass man finally did the driving, you know, and they swapped off.
And one night, the bass man went down in South Africa.
We didn't play in a place.
And we'd move over to the next town where we'd go and check in the motel about daylight.
And then we'd stay there all day, and then we'd see it at night.
So it kind of helped us out.
So our extension was used up.
But the base man, he was down about two or three o'clock in the morning.
And he had some kind of stomach problem.
It required emergency treatment.
And they went to the hospital.
So we put him in the hospital.
And I think he had to be in there several days.
But anyway, that's just one of the little things that you put up with when you're out on the road.
Did y'all go out of state, or did you stay in Texas?
We stayed in Texas with that band.
I had gone to Durango, Colorado with that band.
A member of it, in that band, wanted me to come to Texas.
We stayed in Durango for about a year, and then we came back to Texas.
What year was it that the man from A&M contacted you?
So you were how old then?
I was born in 1912.
Well, so you were 28.
And what was his name?
Well, Murray Evans was the guy who got me down there.
I can't remember the band leader's name.
Excuse me.
All these things, of course, if you need to have that information, you can get it in the yearbook.
Yes.
How did you get to College Station?
What did you bring with you?
Do you remember what it was?
Well, I came dressed in a suit.
And as a matter of fact, after about a day down here with Evan, he said to me, you know, Fred, I don't think you ought to come to New York.
I said, why not?
Well, I didn't ask him that right now, but I said, no, I've always wanted to go to Indiana, and I'm going to stay.
He said, if you want to.
So later on, he did tell me, he said, well, you were dressed like you, you know, you'd given up a good job, but probably hadn't the best clothes on, you know.
And all the guys in the band treated me like I was, you know, maybe a junior or something.
Do you remember what your major was that freshman year?
Well, I started off with it.
And where did you, what dorm were you in?
Here's what happened.
The guys, they would bring me down here, you know.
What was the name?
B-A-U-S-H-A-B-S-E-N. Where was it?
It was up on College Avenue over there in that building.
You may remember where they had the hat shop over there.
That used to be a student's house.
At that time, they didn't have enough housing on the campus.
And you know, the man that started that, the housing thing out there, you know, they had about 14 of those houses down in New Mexico.
At the time when I came to A&M, A&M was growing, and students were staying as far away as they could in Caldwell and places like that to be able to find a house to stay in.
And they commuted.
And we commuted, but this one guy owned a truck, a big bed on the back of it, and we used to ride it, too, in that time.
Now, as a freshman, you were in the Corps of Cadets.
No, I didn't get in because I was old enough to decide not to.
And besides, then we had the Franks, you know, in the uniform.
I came down here, and I was 30 bucks in my pocket.
And it was all that wrecked the situation.
If I had to depend on my finances to keep a place to sleep, I could keep it in the street.
Having no one, you know.
But the books land, you know, in the chorus.
There's chorus out there for the chorus dancers, you know, that .
And then we play for the chorus dancers.
So we'd be playing maybe every Friday night.
Where were those dances held?
In Sabisa.
In Sabisa.
And so you were the pianist?
Yes, I was.
Please try to recall as much as you can the names of the people in the band when you joined it.
Well, you know, that's a long time ago.
I realize I can only remember...
Maybe one man's name.
Who was it?
That was the guy that got me down.
Oh, because he was from my hometown.
I'd known him for a long time.
But in a 16 guy, you know, you don't really know anybody's name very well.
And did a number of them live at the same place you did?
No.
Actually, most of them were corpsmen.
Okay.
And, you know, they played in the bands out there, you know.
Do you remember how much did y'all get paid?
I worked in the English office one time for 25 cents an hour.
And you can see that if I got $5 a dance, you know, those dances, well, I was, like you said, you know, sometimes $5 or $500.
Did you have to pay rent at that boarding house?
No, I didn't.
No.
I had to pay for food.
But it was more or less a kind of a reason.
It was kind of a favorite deal of ours.
They had had two piano men before me, maybe more, I know more than that.
They were brothers.
And one played during history, and then the other kept away.
And then they didn't have anybody else, so that's when they got me.
And they were very, that's tenuous, because piano men are hard to come by.
Now, how did you move the piano around?
Well, we played it.
And so there was a piano there.
Now, when did you go over there to practice?
How often?
I think we rehearsed Monday.
I can't remember whether it was Thursday or Tuesday night.
Glenn Miller, Benny Goodman.
Y'all were most similar to which one of them?
Probably more like Ben Miller.
We played most of his songs.
And then Benny Goodman and the two brothers, Tommy Dorothy and his brother Jimmy, all of them played about the same kind of music.
So we kind of played that kind of thing.
And I can tell you about this.
There used to be something called a six-band night.
And they'd go out and see who was most wanted right there.
So we got the four students that they knew.
They had a show once a week called the six-band night.
And they picked up bands from around the world.
It seemed to be the top of the class.
Do you remember what year that was?
It's probably 41.
And where in Dallas did y'all play?
Was it one of the big hotels?
Yes, I think it was in Dallas.
That's A-D-O-L-P-H-U-S. Adolphus.
But most of us always say Dolphus.
What did you all wear when you were playing?
Suit.
But was it a coat and tie?
Yeah.
We didn't have a uniform on.
did did and you always call the group the aggie land orchestra yeah and about would you do one average one
a concert a week or twice?
No, usually it's one a week because, you know, the chorus, the chorus, people would have their own dances planned.
And they'd have their girlfriends come down.
At that time, we had a railroad theater.
And about 6 o'clock in the afternoon on Friday, they'd go down to the railway station and meet their girls and sing.
And generally, I would say they had already booked them.
How did Aggies and their dates behave at those bands at those dances?
Well, you know, that was when we had those wild dances, you know, and most everybody did.
Jitterbug.
Yeah.
But though
Did they ever get out of line?
Did the Aggies misbehave?
No, not ever.
We didn't have any trouble at all.
And the young ladies, what did they wear to the dances?

as i guess you expect them to you know coming this far you know just because it's a special occasion in their lives they came down from the girls college in tscw yeah cia at first yeah that's right yeah yeah well they'd come down you know i guess they'd get together up there and they
Now when y'all, when the Aggieland Orchestra went somewhere out of town, how did y'all get there?
During the Christmas season, our band leader would book dances all over the hometown
And we used to play every night somewhere.
We'd start out in San Angelo and go out to Lagos and that big spring and Odessa and all these towns in between and we'd just kind of make a circle.
If it was too far, we'd have some other kind of arrangement.
The mother's club had arranged to bed the guys, you know, in various homes.
